summary:
A couple of years back, I did a post about my Daily Carry for college&hellip; Well, I have finished (ish) college, but i still cary a lot of weird and wonderful stuff&hellip; So, this is the update&hellip;
So, the contents are as follows:
  Microsoft SurfaceBook with an i7 processor, 16GB RAM and 512GB Storage, along with the dGPU. Samsung Galaxy Note 3 Beats by Dr. Dre Wireless on ear headphones.

[NOTE] This part 1 in a series of posts. The rest can be found here.
First, a bit of background, and then I will explain what I am currently running in Part 2&hellip;
For the last 15 or so years, I have had at least 2 internet connections in to the house&hellip; 2 of them have always been Cable Modems from NTL, which became UPC, and now is Virgin Media. When I started, i think the modems where 150/50kbit/s and 600/150kb/s, and have steadily increased in speed, currently at 360/36Mbit/s each&hellip; But they have always been somewhat separate, and single thread downloads have always been limited to 1 of the connections&hellip; I have been looking for ways around this for years&hellip;

I mentioned HubiC in my last post, and in it i said that you could use Duplicity for backups. Well, this is how you get it to work&hellip;
First, i am using Ubuntu 14.04 (i think&hellip;). I use Ubuntu in house for a few things:
 its running Tiernan&rsquo;s Comms Closet, GeekPhotographer and Tiernan&rsquo;s Podcast all in house, aswell as being used to build this site. The Web Server and MySQL Server are seperated, MySQL running on Windows, web on Ubuntu&hellip; but thats a different story&hellip; I have a couple of proxy servers running Ubuntu also Other general servers running Ubuntu&hellip; dont ask, cause i cant remember what they do half the time&hellip;  So, Duplicity is a backup application.

Earlier on today, the Raspberry Pi Foundation announced that the Model B will now be shipping with 512Mb RAM as standard, with no price change. I posted the link up on Hacker News and its caused quite a lot of happy people!
So, with the news of extra RAM, its started making me think of more things the Pi could be used for&hellip;
 An Austrian hosting company are offering free Co-Location for Raspberry Pis with a 100Mb/s uplink and 100Gb bandwidth!

